1 — Executive summary
This document is a comprehensive handover for "backend-tbd" — a Node.js + Express backend that powers an assessment platform. It is intended to give a new backend engineer everything needed to understand, run, maintain, and improve the system, including architecture, models, routes, deployment notes, and common troubleshooting steps.

Short description:
- Provides admin/manager/leader/employee roles.
- Invitation-based employee flow (no-login tokenized access).
- Assessment lifecycle: create, start, submit, export (Excel/PDF).
- Question bank CRUD and bulk upload (Excel/CSV).
- Dashboards and role-based analytics.
- File uploads (images, Excel), email sending, and a cron job for cleanup.

This handover expands prior notes into a professionally organized document suitable for printing or PDF delivery.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2 — Goals & audience
Primary goal: enable a backend engineer to onboard quickly and be productive within a day or two.
Audience:
- New backend engineer who will maintain or extend the API
- DevOps or SRE who will deploy and monitor the app
- Product/PM for high-level understanding of capabilities

What this document assumes:
- Familiarity with Node.js and Express
- Basic MongoDB / Mongoose knowledge
- Comfortable with command-line tools and environment variables

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3 — High-level architecture and data flow
3.1 Components
- Entrypoint: src/index.js — environment, DB connect, conditional server start, cron jobs
- App builder: src/app.js — constructs Express app, global middlewares, route mounting
- Controllers: src/controllers/* — business logic and input validation
- Models: src/models/* — Mongoose schemas and methods
- Middlewares: src/middlewares/* — auth checks, file handling, CSV parsing
- Services: src/services/* — email providers, cloudinary, PDF generation, Excel exports
- Utilities: src/utils/* — small helpers, validators

3.2 Data flow examples
- Admin creates assessment:
  POST /api/v1/assessment/start -> protect -> controller creates Assessment document -> returns id

- Employee completes assessment (no-login):
  Employee opens invite link -> employeeAccess middleware validates inviteToken -> controller fetches questions -> employee submits answers -> controller saves Response documents and marks Invitation.used=true

- Export flow:
  Request -> controller queries Response data -> generates Excel (exceljs) or renders HTML and uses Puppeteer to produce PDF -> returns file or stores in cloud and returns download URL

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4 — Tech stack & dependencies
- Node.js (ES modules) & npm
- Express v5
- MongoDB with mongoose
- Authentication: jsonwebtoken
- File uploads: multer
- Email: nodemailer, @sendgrid/mail, resend (check which is wired in controllers)
- Excel/CSV: exceljs, xlsx, csv-parser, json2xls
- PDF: puppeteer + @sparticuz/chromium, pdf-lib
- Image tools: sharp, cloudinary
- Scheduler: node-cron
- Dev tooling: nodemon, eslint

Notes:
- package.json uses "type":"module" — use import/export syntax.
- Puppeteer in serverless environments needs a compatible Chromium binary; @sparticuz/chromium is included to help with that.

