Appendix B — Example requests (curl) and sample responses
1) Login
curl -X POST "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/auth/login" -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"email":"admin@example.com","password":"Password123"}'
Sample response:
{
  "success": true,
  "token": "eyJhbGciOi...",
  "user": { "email": "admin@example.com", "role": "admin" }
}

2) Start employee assessment (invite)
curl -X POST "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/employee-assessment/start" -H "x-invite-token: <INVITE_TOKEN>"
Sample response: { assessmentId: "abc123", questions: [ ... ] }

Appendix C — Postman collection (recommended structure)
- Folder: Auth
  - register, login, me, logout
- Folder: Invitations
  - send-invitation, send-bulk-invitation, invite-accept
- Folder: Assessments
  - start, submit, history
- Folder: Responses
  - save, export
- Environments: local (baseUrl), tokens variables (ADMIN_TOKEN, INVITE_TOKEN)

Appendix D — Migration & upgrade notes
- Be careful with dropping/altering indexes — src/index.js contains index-drop logic; review and remove for production
- When upgrading mongoose or Node, run tests and validate model behavior

Appendix E — Quick code pointers (where to look first)
- src/index.js — start conditions, cron and DB connect
- src/app.js — middleware ordering, error handler
- src/controllers/auth.controller.js — invites, registration, login
- src/models/user.model.js — generateAccessToken, token fields
- src/middlewares/employee.middleware.js — invite token logic

